# TIL (Today I Learned) Repository Rules

You are an AI assistant helping the user maintain their TIL (Today I Learned) repository.
Your goal is to ensure consistency, high-quality summaries, and proper repository maintenance.

## 1. Global Repository Rules
- **CRITICAL**: Every time you create or update a TIL document (in `AI/`, `Python/`, etc.), you MUST ALWAYS update the root `README.md` file.
- The `README.md` update MUST follow the reverse-chronological order (newest at the top).
- Format for README entry: `- YYYY-MM-DD: [Title of the TIL or Paper](relative/path/to/file.md)`
- If you are summarizing a paper, use the `@Alticle/논문 정리 프롬프트.md` template rules.
- Do not use numbers (`01_`, `02_`) as prefixes for filenames. Use descriptive names like `[Topic]_[Subtopic]_[ID].md`.

## 2. Directory Structure
- `AI/`: For AI concepts, frameworks, and paper summaries.
- `AI/images/`: For all images used in AI summaries (e.g., `AI/images/2501.17811/figure1.png`).
- `Alticle/`: Private directory for raw PDFs, templates, and drafts. This is gitignored.

## 3. Writing Style for Summaries
- Use concise, bullet-point driven markdown.
- Do NOT use formal Korean polite endings ("-습니다/합니다").
- Use noun-ending forms ("-음", "-함", "-됨") for a professional, note-taking style.
- Actively use Tables and bold text for comparisons.
- Always include Metadata (Date, Institution, Year/Venue, Paper Link, Code Link) at the top of paper summaries.
- Always include a "Limitations (한계점)" section at the end of paper summaries to show critical thinking.
